Flash Sale Example

Suppose:

100 iPhones available

Flash sale starts.

1 million users click BUY simultaneously

If all requests directly hit DB:

UPDATE inventory
SET stock = stock - 1

then:

huge DB contention
lock waits
retries
DB crash possibility




So real systems use multiple layers.


________________________________

Step 1 — Redis Atomic Stock Check

Stock stored in Redis:

stock:iphone = 100

When user clicks BUY:
DECR stock:iphone

Redis operation is atomic.

So:

only first 100 users succeed
others instantly rejected

This prevents:

overselling


________________________________

Step 2 — Queue Requests

Successful users placed into queue:

Kafka / RabbitMQ

Why?

Instead of:
1M requests hitting DB together

queue smooths traffic.

________________________________

Step 3 — Sequential Order Processing

Order workers consume queue gradually.

Example:

Worker 1 processes UserA
Worker 2 processes UserB

Now DB load controlled.

________________________________

Step 4 — DB Update

Now final inventory updated safely.

Possible approaches:

Optimistic Locking
UPDATE inventory
SET stock=99, version=6
WHERE version=5;

Good when contention manageable.



Pessimistic Locking
SELECT * FROM inventory
WHERE item='iphone'
FOR UPDATE;

Used for strict correctness.

Ensures:

no simultaneous modification

________________________________


Why cant we dorectly use DB locks - pessimistoc locking for updates


If 1M users directly wait on DB locks:
DB becomes bottleneck
Too many blocked transactions.

________________________________

So systems:

filter traffic at Redis
serialize via queues
use DB locking only at final stage




Final Architecture
Users
  ↓
Redis Atomic Counter
  ↓
Queue (Kafka)
  ↓
Order Workers
  ↓
DB with locking
  ↓
Order Confirmed



Main Idea


Redis
fast stock reservation

Queue
smooth traffic spikes

DB Locking
final correctness guarantee
